  "prompt": "How did Benchling get started?",
  "response": "Benchling, a life sciences R&D cloud platform, was founded in 2012 by Ashu Singhal, Cory Li, Sajith Wickramasekara, and Srivatsan Srinivasan. The company originated from the founders' experiences as students at MIT, where they observed the inefficiencies and challenges researchers faced in managing and organizing scientific data, particularly in the fields of biology and life sciences.\n\nThe initial vision was to create a platform that would digitize and streamline laboratory workflows, making it easier for researchers to design experiments, track data, and collaborate. At the time, much of the scientific data was still managed using paper notebooks and fragmented software tools, which hindered productivity and reproducibility. \n\nThe founders saw an opportunity to develop a unified, cloud-based platform tailored to the needs of life scientists. They built Benchling to provide tools for tasks like DNA sequence design, molecular cloning, and data management, all integrated into a single platform that could be accessed from anywhere.\n\nBenchling started as a small team working out of Y Combinator, a startup accelerator, which helped them refine their product and business model. Over time, the platform gained traction in academic labs, biotech companies, and pharmaceutical firms, growing into a widely-used solution for R&D in the life sciences.\n\nToday, Benchling continues to expand its capabilities, focusing on accelerating scientific discovery and improving collaboration across the industry.",
